        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Sumter S. C. 4 Mch 1872.<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd S. Morais<lb/>
            Philadelphia Pa.<lb/>
            Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I take the liberty of<lb/> asking you to enlighten me upon<lb/> a point of Jewish Law.<lb/></p>
            <p>My son&#44; aged 13&#44; has<lb/> received a present from a friend&#44; of a<lb/> nice gun&#44; with which he has<lb/> been shooting birds.  As I live<lb/> &#34;Kosher&#34; and do not eat even<lb/> poultry except when killed by<lb/> myself or other person qualified<lb/> to kill&#44; I have stopped the use of<lb/> the gun until I can learn what<lb/> the Law is.<lb/></p>
            <p>My view of the case&#44; is<lb/> that the general prohibition<lb/> against &#34;killing&#44;&#34; as contained<lb/> in the Decalogue&#44; has no ex&#45;<lb/>ceptions&#44; outside of the Law<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>itself&#59; that is to say&#44; we may<lb/> kill men in self&#45;<sic>defence</sic>&#44; or in<lb/> defence<sic></sic> of our families or our<lb/> country&#58; and we may kill animals for food only&#44; or in<lb/> self&#45;<sic>defence</sic> &#40;as above&#41;.  But it<lb/> seems to me&#44; that the killing of<lb/> any animal for mere amuse&#45;<lb/>ment&#44; is a vicious action&#44; and<lb/> a <sic>violaxion</sic> of Law.<lb/></p>
            <p>A reply will be<lb/> gratefully received.<lb/>
            By Your obt svt<lb/>
            Chas. H. Moise<lb/></p>
            <p>P.S.<lb/>
            I have seen your beautiful and<lb/> richly merited offering&#44; in memory<lb/> of Miss Cornelia Hart&#44; and read<lb/> it with tears.  C. H. M<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>Return to CHAS. H. MOISE <del>&#38; CO.&#44;</del><lb/>
                SUMTER&#44; S. C.<lb/>
                if not delivered within 10 days.<lb/></p>
            <p>Revd S. Morais<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/>
                Pa&#58;<lb/></p>

        </body>
